Olufemi Atoyebi, Abuja The Chairman of the Board of Management of the University College Hospital, Ibadan, Shettima Bagudu, has tested negative for coronavirus after being at an isolation centre for several days. The chairman fell ill at the beginning of the hospital’s last board meeting on March 24, 2020, and was promptly admitted for treatment. It was later confirmed that he had tested positive for the virus. On April 8, he was tested to confirm if he had been negative but the result came out positive again and he remained in the isolation centre for further treatment. READ ALSO: Gunmen kill civil defence officer in Benue The Public Relations Officer of the hospital, Toye Akinrinlola, in a statement on Sunday confirmed that the chairman had finally tested negative upon further tests. He said, “I have the pleasure to announce that after three weeks of being in quarantine, the Chairman of the Board of Management of the University College Hospital, Ibadan, Alhaji Shettima Bagudu, has tested negative to the coronavirus. “Two tests were carried out on him and both returned negative. With this, he now has a clean bill of health. “The Chairman has urged Nigerians to observe the guidelines laid down by the World Health Organization and the National Center for Disease Control. He thanked the UCH community for their support and encouragement during the trying period. “He also expressed his appreciation to the CMD, Prof Jesse Otegbayo, the management of the Hospital and all the medical personnel that attended to him while in the quarantine.”